{"key":"processedPost-13785530","value":{"id":13785530,"first":13781137,"last":17096033,"when":1295027736,"utime":"01/14/11 07:55 PM","content":"Cubes are not native to California, so no.<br /><br />A day/night temperature fluctuation is a major pinning trigger, and moist perlite in a shotgun terrarium will not dry out for a month or two, much longer than a cropping cycle.<br /><br />Standing water is bad, period.<br /><br />Don't heat a terrarium.&nbsp; Heat the area it is in if necessary.<br /><br />In addition, you MUST mist.&nbsp; If you have no evaporation of moisture from your substrate, it won't pin.&nbsp; If you do have evaporation of moisture from your substrate, it will pin, but that lost moisture must be replaced by misting.&nbsp; Spraying the sides of a terrarium is a waste of water.&nbsp; The plastic doesn't need moisture, but the substrate does.&nbsp; New growers obsess on humidity, while <i>loss of&nbsp; moisture</i> is the number one pinning trigger.&nbsp; Every new grower gets this wrong on his first few grows, and they always dispute this fact when it's&nbsp; pointed out to them.&nbsp; Live and learn.<br />RR","title":"Re: Question on standing water in the fruiting chamber."}}